<section xml:id="sec-exponential-equations" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Exponential Equations</title>
  
  <introduction>
    <definition>
      <title>Exponential Equation</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          An <term>exponential equation</term> is an equation with a variable in the exponent.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
  </introduction>
  
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-solving-exponential-equations">
    <title>Solving Exponential Equations Using Common Bases</title>
    
    <p>
      Some simple exponential equations can be solved by using the intuitive fact that if two powers with the same base are equal, then their exponents must be equal. In other words,
    </p>

    <md>
      <mrow>\boxed{\text{If $b^x=b^y$, then $x=y$}}</mrow>
    </md>
    
    <p>
      This means that if we can write both sides of an exponential equation as a power of the same base, then we can set their exponents equal (<alert>equate exponents</alert>), resulting in a simpler equation that we can solve.
    </p>
    
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>Rewrite both sides using a common base.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Simplify using exponent laws.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Set the exponents equal.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Solve the resulting equation.</p>
      </li>
    </ol>
    
    <p>
      The resulting equation could be linear, quadratic, or some other type of equation.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      Sometimes, both sides can be written as a power of multiple numbers, which result in the same solution.
    </p>
  </subsection>
  
